# TEC.ERP Documentation

See `docs/00_ENGINEERING_PRINCIPLES.md` EP-003 and `docs/19` §94, §2521.

## Documentation Before Development

No implementation starts before consulting the relevant official specification. Read the doc, then code.

## Continuous Documentation

Documentation and implementation evolve together (QUALITY-003, `docs/19` §94). When code changes affect:

| Change type | Consult / align with |
|-------------|---------------------|
| Business logic | `docs/15_ERP_FUNCTIONAL_SPECIFICATION.md` |
| UI screens | `docs/16_UI_BLUEPRINT.md` |
| Data model | `docs/17_DATABASE_SCHEMA.md` |
| API endpoints | `docs/18_API_SPECIFICATION.md` |
| Engineering process | `docs/19_CURSOR_MASTER_BUILD_SPECIFICATION.md` |
| Sprint scope | `docs/20_MVP_IMPLEMENTATION_BACKLOG.md` |

## Protecting Official Docs

- **Never modify `docs/`** without explicit user approval
- If implementation reveals a spec gap, **flag it** and propose a doc update — do not silently drift
- Research and market analysis stay separate from official product docs (EP-005)

## What to Document in Code Work

- Meaningful commit messages describing the logical change (`docs/19` §13)
- PR summary: objective, impacted modules, testing evidence, doc alignment (`docs/19` §14)
- Approval Gate report for completed phases (`docs/19` §61)
- Database migrations documented and tested before production (`docs/19` §79)

## Allowed Write Targets

Source code, tests, configuration, and engineering notes outside `docs/` — unless the user explicitly requests an official doc update.
